flowRoot.flowPara: The Real-Time eXperiment Interface: a closed-loop data acquisition system with sub-millisecond latencies for electrophysiology.
A. George1, Y. Patel2, F. Ortega1, J. White3, D. Christini1, A. Dorval3, R. Butera2;

The Real-time eXperiment Interface, or RTXI, is a closed-loop, hard real-time data acquisition and control system for electophysiology. It is an interection between many open-source initiatives that provides a mature, extensible framework for designing and carrying out experiments. It can be used to simultaneously handle multichannel data acquisition through a growing set of hardware, computational models of moderate complexity, and recording to disk all at sub-millisecond latencies.
1Weill Cornell Medical College, New York, NY, 2Georgia Institute of Technology, Atlanta, GA, and 3The University of Utah, Salt Lake City, UT
RTXI is free and runs on almost any modern desktop. All that's needed is a compatible data acquisition card. To date, it has been used in over 60 labs aroun the world.
Note: more complex models need more powerful computers for RTXI to work in real time
The latest version of RTXI, v2.0, is freely available online. Users can download:
- the official live CD on our website (http://www.rtxi.org)
- the sources on our GitHub repository (https://github.com/rtxi)
On our sites, you will also find:
- tutorials for installing RTXI and customizing modules
- places to report bugs, submit feature requests, contact us
- an all-RTXI conference for users old, new, and in-between
- focused on RTXI for real-time, closed loop ephys research

Modules can be configured to any desired level of complexity, though needs for increased computation time limits how fast the real-time subsystem can run.
Using RTXI for Closed-loop, Real-time Experiments
The set of loaded modules become a workspace, capable of executing protocols, plotting and recording data, all within a closed-loop framework.
Pictured here are the noise-generator, oscilloscope, and performance measurement modules.
There are currently over 50 RTXI modules available. The full selection is available on our GitHub repository.
